05298nam a2201009Ia 9780691257440DE-B159720240426104009.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240426t20242024nju    fo  d z      eng d  a97806912574407 a10.1515/97806912574402doi  a(DE-B1597)677980  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 4aND553.M7bS57 2024 7aART0160002bisacsh04a759.4223/eng/202311221 aSiegel, Harmon, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aPainting with Monet /cHarmon Siegel. 1aPrinceton, NJ : bPrinceton University Press, c[2024] 4c©2024  a1 online resource (312 p.) :b183 color + 13 b/w illus.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tINTRODUCTION: The Reality of Others -- tONE What Painting Together Makes Possible -- tTWO Boudin’s Beholder -- tTHREE Jongkind’s Originality -- tFOUR Bazille’s Individuality -- tFIVE Renoir’s Society -- tSIX Sisley’s Perspective -- tSEVEN Manet’s Humanity -- tCONCLUSION -- tAcknowledgments -- tAbbreviations for Frequently Cited Sources -- tNotes -- tIndex -- tPhoto Credits0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aA major reassessment of the methods and meaning of impressionismAt pivotal moments in his career, Claude Monet would go out with a fellow artist, plant his easel beside his friend’s, and paint the same scene. Painting with Monet closely examines pairs of such works, showing how attention to this practice raises tantalizing new questions about Monet’s art and about impressionism as a movement.Is impressionist painting an objective attempt to capture reality as it really is? Or is it a subjective expression of the artist’s unique way of perceiving things? How can artists create a movement without conformity extinguishing individuality? Harmon Siegel reveals how Monet explored problems like these in concrete, practical ways while painting alongside his teachers, Eugène Boudin and Johan Barthold Jongkind; his friends, Frédéric Bazille and Pierre-Auguste Renoir; and his hero, Édouard Manet. At a time of major cultural upheavals, these artists asked how we can know reality beyond our personal perception. Siegel provides new insights into the aesthetic, philosophical, and ethical stakes for these painters as they responded to a rapidly changing society.Beautifully illustrated, Painting with Monet sheds critical light on how Monet and his fellow impressionists, painting side by side, professed their capacity to know the world and affirmed their belief in what Siegel calls the reality of others.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aImpressionism (Art)zFrance. 0aPlein air paintingzFrancexHistoryy19th century. 7aART / Individual Artists / General.2bisacsh  aApartment Interior.  aCamille Corot.  aCavell.  aCharles Baudelaire.  aClaude Monet.  aCorot.  aCourbet.  aEdouard Manet.  aForest of Symbols.  aFrederic Bazille.  aFrench art.  aFrench impressionism.  aFrench painting.  aGawkers.  aHegel.  aManet.  aMonet.  aMonet’s Minutes.  aMonet’s early work.  aMonet’s rule.  aPaul Cezanne.  aPhilosophy by Other Means.  aRenoir.  aSisley.  aaesthetics.  aassociation of nineteenth century French art historians.  acollege art association.  acomposition.  aeugene boudin.  aimpressionism.  aimpressionist painting.  ajohan barthold jongkind.  amonet’s garden.  anineteenth century painting.  anineteenth-century art.  apaint what you really see.  aphilosophy of art.  apierre-auguste Renoir.  apractice.  arenoir’s society.  aside by side painting.  asocial practice.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPrinceton University Press Complete eBook-Package 2024z978311074975540uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780691